
CREATION:
CREATE TABLE <table_name> (
	<column1_name> <datatype> [additional parameteres] PRIMARY_KEY,
	<column2_name> <datatype> [additional parameteres],
	...
	<columnN_name> <datatype> [additional parameteres]
);

TEXT -> string
INT -> numeric
DECIMAL -> has decimal point
NOT NULL -> to insert a row, you need to fill in this space

example:
CREATE TABLE user (
	user_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
  	name TEXT NOT NULL,
  	pass TEXT NOT NULL,
  	age DECIMAL(2, 0) NOT NULL
);

(any string/text is with single quotes)
DECIMAL(2, 0) means it can be 2 digits, and 0 digits to the right of the decimal point




ALTER:

ALTER TABLE <table_name>
ADD <columnN_name> <datatype> [additional parameters];

ADD -> adds a new column, updating the table structure

example:
ALTER TABLE user
ADD email TEXT NOT NULL;

altering a cloumn: (example, altering age to be a string) (sqlite doesnt allow)
ALTER TABLE user
ALTER COLUMN age TEXT;




DROP:
DROP TABLE <table_name>;
(BE VERY CAREFUL!!!!!!!, "DROP <table_name>;" DELETES THE TABLE AND ALL ITS DATA!!!!!!!!!!!)

example:
DROP TABLE user;




INSERT:
INSERT INTO <table_name> (<column2>, <column1>, ...)
VALUES (<value2>, <value1>, ...), (<value2>, <value1>, ...);
(as long as the column corresponds to the value, everything is good)
(can insert multiple rows in the same sql command)

example:
INSERT INTO user (user_id, name, pass, age)
VALUES (
	1,
	'Bruno',
	'safe_pass_lol',
	22
);



DELETE:
DELETE FROM <table_name>
WHERE <condition>;
(BE VERY CAREFUL!!!!!!!, "DELETE FROM <table_name>;" without filtering condition deletes all rows!!!!!!!!!!!)

example
DELETE FROM user
WHERE age < 24;




UPDATE ... SET ...:

UPDATE <table_name>
SET <column1> = <new_value1>,
	<column2> = <new_value2>,
	...
WHERE <condition>;
(BE VERY CAREFUL!!!!!!!, "UPDATE ... SET ...;" without filtering condition updates all rows!!!!!!!!!!!)


example:
UPDATE user
SET pass = 'yet_another_safe_pass',
	name = 'another_name'
WHERE age > 24;





